Case Study: The myogenesis program drives clonal selection and drug resistance in rhabdomyosarcoma

Kayla Interdonanto

Roswell Park Comprehensive Cancer Center
Kayla.Morrell@RoswellPark.org

4 November 2022

Source: vignettes/hca-74e2ef9d-7c9f-418c-b281-7fb38f3b1571.Rmd
hca-74e2ef9d-7c9f-418c-b281-7fb38f3b1571.Rmd

Setup

Load useful packages

library(HCACaseStudies)
library(hca)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

Project information

Set the project id

project_id <- "74e2ef9d-7c9f-418c-b281-7fb38f3b1571"

Display information about the project

project_information(project_id)
## Title
##   The myogenesis program drives clonal selection and drug resistance in
##   rhabdomyosarcoma
## Contributors (unknown order; any role)
##   Michael,A,Dyer, Rachel Schwartz
## Description
##   Rhabdomyosarcoma (RMS) is the most soft tissue sarcoma of childhood
##   and histologically mimics developing skeletal muscle. To better
##   understand RMS, we performed single-cell RNA-seq of one embryonal
##   subtype RMS (ERMS) and one alveolar subtype RMS (ARMS). We expanded
##   our observations by performing single-nucleus RNA-seq of 18 patient
##   tumors (12 ERMS, 6 ARMS). All 18 of these tumors were used to
##   generate orthotopic patient-derived xenografts, and we performed
##   single-cell RNA-seq of all 18 O-PDXs to compare heterogeneity between
##   the original tumor and the patient-derived model. 15 of the O-PDXs
##   underwent lentiviral barcoding, and lineage could be tracked using a
##   separate dial-out PCR step during the single-cell RNA-seq workflow.
##   We performed single-cell RNA-seq of an ex vivo organoid, showing that
##   we can preserve heterogeneity in this model. We expanded our study to
##   the epigenetic level by using single-cell ATAC-sequencing of 7
##   O-PDXs. Finally, we longitudinally tracked shifts in heterogeneity in
##   an O-PDX model treated with chemotherapy. Overall design: We
##   performed single-cell RNA-seq from 2 patient RMS tumors, 18 O-PDXs,
##   and 1 organoid. Additionally, we performed single-nucleus RNA-seq
##   from 18 patient RMS tumors and single-cell ATAC-seq from 7 O-PDXs. We
##   also provide dialout PCR data from 15 RMS O-PDX that were used for
##   lentiviral barcode experiments to track clonal lineages within
##   O-PDXs.
## DOI
##   10.1016/j.devcel.2022.04.003
## URL
##   https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S153458072200243X?via%3Dihub
## Project
##   https://data.humancellatlas.org/explore/projects/74e2ef9d-7c9f-418c-b281-7fb38f3b1571

Conventions

Statistics calculated locally use local.* for column names, e.g., local.cellCount.

Data processing

Project & samples

Create a filter to identify the project

project_filter <- filters(projectId = list(is = project_id))

Find the project

p <- projects(project_filter, as = "tibble_expanded")

## create `files2` with just the files needed for count-matrix
## analysis

files2 <- files1 |>
    filter(fileFormat == "tar")

Retrieve and cache locally all files needed to construct a gene x cell count matrix.

tar_file <-
    files2 |>
    files_download() |>
    setNames(files2 |> pull(name))

This is a ‘tar’ archive of GSM files; untar these to a temporary location

## what files are in the tar?
tar_files <- untar(tar_file, list = TRUE)

untar(tar_file, exdir = exdir)

Parse the file names to create a tibble with local file path, file type, and sample id

local_files <-
    tibble(
        local.filePath = file.path(exdir, tar_files),
        ## local.fileType becomes one of barcodesPath, genesPath, matrixPath
        local.fileType = sub(".*_([[:alpha:]]*).*", "\\1Path", tar_files),
        local.sampleId = sub("([^_]*).*", "\\1", tar_files)
    ) |>
    ## each 'sampleId' has a barcodesPath, genesPath, and matrixPath
    pivot_wider(
        names_from = local.fileType,
        names_prefix = "local.",
        values_from = "local.filePath"
    )
## 64 samples
local_files |>
    mutate(across(ends_with("Path"), basename))

Count matrix

Create a dgCMatrix sparse matrix (defined in the Matrix package). Save it in the package cache for re-use across R sessions.

## Remove files with NA in featuresPath and/or barcodesPath
local_files2 <- local_files |>
    filter(!(is.na(local.featuresPath)))
gene_and_cell_counts <-
    local_files2 |>
    csv_tsv_count_lines("local.sampleId", "local.barcodesPath") |>
    rename(local.cellCount = local.lines) |>
    csv_tsv_count_lines("local.sampleId", "local.featuresPath") |>
    rename(local.geneCount = local.lines)
gene_and_cell_counts |>
    select(local.sampleId, local.geneCount, local.cellCount)

sample_data <-
    ## from the hca sample annotation...
    s |>
    select(
        where(column_is_informative) & where(is.atomic)
    ) |>
    ## ...and local computations, e.g.,gene and cell counts
    left_join(
        gene_and_cell_counts |>
        select(local.sampleId, local.cellCount, local.geneCount),
        by = c(samples.id = "local.sampleId")
    )
